atqut et...certee the same form in 19, l. 143 cf. 32‚ll. 9 sq. Atqui has two uses; it introduces (r) a new step in an argument which is being unfolded step by step as here and 32, l. 9, or (2) a mort, or a statement in contrast with what immediately precedes (so in 19,l.14). Qui in atqui is an old ablative (used as adverb) of quis the indefinite pronoun, as qui (hom) is an old abl. of quis the interrogative pronoun. The indefinite qui meant originally (like the enclitic πως) “somehow or other,'' but in compounds ceased to have any precise force. It is attached to many words in early Latin, but in later Latin we only find atqui, alt'oqut', amm utqui [Lucretiusl. The forms atquin etc. are erroneous.
